const letterParagraph = `Before I even start talking about dates, fights, silence, or growth — I just want to say this first: you are not just someone in my life. You became a part of it so slowly and so deeply that I didn’t even realize when you stopped being “just a friend” and started being my comfort, my habit, my safe place. You became the person I wanted to tell everything to. The one whose opinion mattered a little more. The one whose presence could fix my mood without even trying.

And that’s why when we fight, it doesn’t feel small. It never feels small. Because when someone ordinary leaves your day, it’s manageable. But when you leave — even for a few days — something feels incomplete. There’s this quiet emptiness. This missing piece in my routine. I still do everything I normally do… but it feels different.

We have fought more times than I can count. Not silly little disagreements — but real fights. Fights where emotions were high, words were sharp, and both of us felt misunderstood. And every time, there was this moment where it felt like maybe this is it. Maybe this is the fight that ends us.

Before 14th April 2025, we were already intense. Already close. Already attached in ways we probably didn’t fully admit. But that day… something shifted. That fight wasn’t about just one thing. It was built-up emotions. Expectations. Hurt. The feeling of not being heard. I remember sitting there after it happened, trying to convince myself I was fine. Trying to act like I didn’t care. But deep down, I cared too much. I kept replaying everything in my head. Wondering where it went wrong. Wondering if you were thinking about me too. Wondering if you were missing me but just too stubborn to say it.

The silence after 14th April hurt more than the fight itself. Because when we fight, at least we’re talking. But when we stop talking? That’s when it feels like something is breaking quietly.

And yet… we found our way back.

We didn’t make a big dramatic speech. We didn’t suddenly become perfect. But we chose to come back. And that choice meant everything to me.

Then 1st November 2025 happened.

Before that date, we had already survived things. I thought maybe we had learned enough. But November tested us differently. That fight carried weight. It wasn’t just anger — it was pain. It was feeling like we were standing on opposite sides of something we didn’t know how to fix. And when we stop talking that time, it felt heavier than ever before.

Two months.

Two entire months of no contact.

Do you know how long two months feel when you’re used to talking to someone almost every day? It feels endless. It feels like learning to live without something that became natural to you. I would see something funny and instinctively want to send it to you. I would go through something important and feel the absence of not being able to tell you. And at night, when everything is quiet, that’s when I felt it the most — the missing conversations, the missing comfort.

And yes, jealousy grew in those two months. I would see you laughing with other people. Talking normally. Living your life. And a small part of me would feel insecure. I would think, “Maybe he doesn’t need me the way I need him.” I never said it out loud. I kept my pride. But inside, I was scared. Scared of being replaced. Scared of becoming just a chapter instead of a constant.

But even through that fear, even through that hurt, there was something inside me that refused to accept that we were over. Because no matter how angry I was, I still wanted you in my life.

And when we finally sorted things after those two months, it wasn’t perfect. It was careful. Fragile. Two people trying again. But it felt like breathing after holding it in for too long.

Then came 11th January 2026.

By then, we had history. We had scars. We had lessons. And still, a misunderstanding managed to hurt us again. That day we blocked each other — the only time we ever did — it felt extreme. It felt like we were both protecting our hearts. Like we were saying, “If I can’t handle this, I’ll shut it out.”

But blocking you didn’t stop me from thinking about you. It didn’t stop me from missing you. It didn't stop me from wondering if you were okay. If anything, it made everything louder. Because when someone matters that much, you can’t just switch it off.

What makes me emotional isn’t that we fought on those dates.

It’s that despite 14th April 2025…
Despite 1st November 2025…
Despite 11th January 2026…

We are still here.

We came back after weeks.
We came back after months.
We came back even after blocking each other.

And every time we came back, we weren’t the same. We were a little more aware. A little more careful. A little more mature. We learned how heavy silence feels. We learned how painful ego can be. We learned that sometimes love — even in friendship — means swallowing pride.

You’ve seen me cry. You’ve seen me overthink. You’ve seen me act strong when I wasn’t. You’ve seen the insecure side of me, the jealous side, the dramatic side. And you stayed.

And I’ve seen you too — your stubbornness, your silence when you’re overwhelmed, the way you act like nothing affects you when it does. And I stayed.

And here’s the part I don’t say enough:

I don’t want this to be temporary.

I don’t want us to be one of those stories where people say, “We used to be so close.” I don’t want to look back at you as a memory. I want to look beside me years from now and still see you there — maybe arguing with me about something stupid, maybe making fun of me, maybe telling me I’m overreacting — but still there.

I want us to grow, to change, to build our lives… and still choose each other. I want us to handle misunderstandings better. I want us to talk instead of going silent. I want us to fight less but love stronger.

I want forever. Not a perfect forever. But a real one. The kind where we survive storms instead of running from them.

You are not just my best friend. You are the person whose absence shakes me. The one I get jealous over because I care too deeply. The one I argue with because your opinion matters. The one I can’t stay away from even when I try.

So on your birthday, I’m not just wishing you happiness.

I’m wishing us strength.
Strength to communicate.
Strength to forgive faster.
Strength to not let ego win.
Strength to choose each other again and again.

Happy Birthday to the boy who became my habit, my comfort, my chaos, my lesson, my jealousy, my safe place, and my constant comeback.

No matter how much we change.
No matter how many fights come.
No matter how life tests us.

I still want you in my life.
Not sometimes.
Not temporarily.
But always.

And I hope that years from now, when we look back at April, November, and January… we won’t feel pain.

We’ll smile and say,
“We almost lost each other… but we didn’t.”`;

